After completing the course, students should be able to:
1. understand the homeostatic controls in our body using the endocrine system;
2. understand how polypeptide hormones and lipid soluble hormones act on their target cells to activate various intracellular signalling pathways;
3. understand the concepts of hormonal control via feedback mechanisms;
4. understand the etiology and diagnosis of diseases from hormone defects, such as gigantism and Cushing Syndrome.

By the end of the course, students will be able to appreciate the complexes of hormonal control of growth, metabolism,reproduction and development.

Objectives for students development:
1. students will be able to understand the special terms in endocrine systems and hormone, so that they will be able to read papers or journal articles in the area of endocrinology and molecular endocrinology;
2. students will be able to understand how we may design experiments to examine the functions and actions of hormones; and 3. students be able to work with peers to discuss and understand the basic mechanisms and actions of hormones in our endocrine system.

Objectives of the course:
Objectives of this course are to elaborate the chemical structures and biological functions of hormones in vertebrates with special emphasis on human subjects to life science students in their senior years. The organization and operation of differenthypothalamus-pituitary-peripheral endocrine gland axes will be discussed. Basic concepts of molecular actions of hormones are also covered. Students are expected to work as group for studying and learn how to read simple journal articles.

After completing the course, students should be able to:
- have an in-depth knowledge of the key features of the immune system;
- comprehend the integrated nature of the immune system;
- understand the molecular basis for generation of antibody diversity, immune response, self-tolerance and disorders in the immune system;
- appreciate the relevance of the immune system in our daily lives & the applications in biotechnology;
- have developed competence in accessing & reviewing scientific literature, and critical appraisal of information;
- develop generic skills such as critical thinking, writing and lifelong learning skills.

Upon the completion of this course, students should be able to:
1. Apply their knowledge of cancer biology and related skills in real-life situations;
2. Sharpen their problem-solving abilities;
3. Strengthen their organizational power;
4. Develop effective communicative and interpersonal skills through group work;
5. Disseminate cancer-related information in a clear, concise and logical manner;
6. Create innovative ideas and methods to solve problems in the cancer research field
7. Appreciate the advantages of cooperative learning;
8. Become an effective member in group dynamics; and
9. Accept new challenges and independent responsibilities.

After taking this course, students are expected to be able to:
1. understand WHO definition of health;
2. understand the definition of functional foods and their application in prevention of chronic diseases including obesity, heart diseases, diabetes mellitus, hypertension, cancer ;
3. understand the principle of Traditional Chinese medicine and its application in nutrition;
4. combine both functional foods and traditional Chinese medicine to decrease the risk of chronic diseases.

Knowledge outcomes:
1. Acquire ability to comprehend the implication and application of genetic concepts in plant biotechnology;
2. Acquire core knowledge on transgenic technologies related to plant biotechnology, with more detailed knowledge on new techniques such as marker-free, gene silencing and RNA interference, and gene editing;
3. Acquire knowledge on potential applications of plant biotechnology;
4. Acquire an educated understanding on the industrial prospective and safety concerns of plant biotechnology.
Skills outcomes:
5. Acquire skills in literature survey using various sources including effective usage of information technologies and web-based searches;
6. Acquire good analytical and oral communication skills via class project presentation;
7. Acquire good problem solving skill via course assessment. Values and attribute outcomes:
8. Acquire a positive attitude toward plant biotechnology;
9. Acquire an educated mind and responsible attitude to judge the pros and cons of various applications of plant biotechnology to the human society and natural environment.

The students will learn:
1. Basic concepts on statistical theories, probability models, and hypothesis testing;
2. Using R to perform routine statistical computation;
3. Running the Python programming environment and scripting with the language.

